02820cam a22003854a 20180607005504.0m     o  d        cr unu||||||||170117s2017    miu     o      00 0 eng d  z2016042827  a9780472122707  a0472122703  a9780472130306q(hardback)  a0472130307q(print)7 a10.3998/mpub.3704206  aMiUbengcMiU00aPN2245.JbN38 201700a792.0973/090342231 aNathans, Heather S.10aHideous characters and beautiful pagans :bperforming Jewish identity on the antebellum American stage /cHeather S. Nathans. 1aAnn Arbor :bUniversity of Michigan Press,c2017.  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  aIncludes bibliographical references and index.  a"While battling negative stereotypes, American Jews carved out new roles for themselves within the first theatrical entertainments in America. Jewish citizens were active as performers, playwrights, critics, managers, and theatrical shareholders, and often tied their involvement in these endeavors to the patriotic rhetoric of the young republic as they struggled to establish themselves in the new nation. Examining play texts, theatrical reviews, political discourse, and public performances of Jewish rights and rituals, Hideous Characters and Beautiful Pagans argues that Jewish stage types shed light on our understanding of the status of Jewish Americans during a critical historical period. Using an eclectic range of sources including theatrical reviews, diaries, letters, cartoons, portraiture, tax records, rumors flying around the tavern, and more, Heather S. Nathans has listened for the echoes of vanished audiences who witnessed and responded to these stereotypes onstage, from the earliest appearance of Shylock on an American stage in 1752 to Jewish theater artists on the eve of the Civil War. The book integrates social, political, and cultural histories, with an examination of those texts (both dramatic and literary) that shaped the stage Jew"--cProvided by publisher.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aTheaterxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTheater and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewsxIdentityzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJews in the theaterzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher.40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.3704206